      "text": "The British demonstrated during World War II how a government can effectively steer to radically transform the economy. The government did not intervene in individual businesses at that time, but continued to leave it up to owners and managers to decide how they wanted to run their businesses internally. The government only determined what was produced in the first place – and how much. The factories were then allocated the necessary labor and raw materials to meet government [[Goal]]s. The British government thus steered indirectly by allocating rare resources in a targeted manner.\n"
